\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. C. lanatus} (Thunb.) Mansfeld,{\i  Kulturpfl.} ({\i Beih}.){\b  2}: 421 (1959) ({\i C. vulgaris} Schrader,{\i  Colocynthis citrullus} (L.) O. Kuntze). Annual. Stems c. 10 mm in diameter, densely villous. Leaves 8-20 × 5-15 cm, ovate in outline, pinnatisect, with lobed segments. Calyx-lobes narrowly lanceolate; corolla-lobes c. 15 mm, ovate-oblong, obtuse. Ovary densely lanate. Fruit c. 25 cm in diameter, subglobose or ellipsoid, smooth, greenish; pulp red, succulent. {\i Widely cultivated in S. Europe for its edible fruits} ({\i water-melon}). ({\i S. Africa.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   {\b 2. C. colocynthis} (L.) Schrader, {\i Linnaea}{\b  12}: 414 (1838) ({\i Colocynthis vulgaris} Schrader). Perennial. Stems c. 2 mm in diameter, hispid. Leaves 5-12 × 3-8 cm, 1- to 2-pinnatisect with 3-5 sinuate-lobed segments. Calyx-lobes subulate; corollalobes c. 5 mm, ovate, acute. Ovary sparsely hispid. Fruit c. 4 cm, globose, smooth, yellow; pericarp dry.{\i  S. part of the Mediterranean region; cultivated elsewhere for its purgative fruits and often naturalized.} Gr Hs Si [Hu It Rm]. ({\i Arid regions of N. Africa and Asia}.)
